# Conventional Commits

Use Conventional Commits for every commit message.

Format:

```text
<type>[optional scope]: <imperative summary>
```

Allowed types:

- `feat`: user-visible feature or capability
- `fix`: bug fix
- `refactor`: behavior-preserving code restructuring
- `test`: tests only
- `docs`: documentation only
- `chore`: maintenance with no runtime behavior change
- `build`: build system or dependency changes
- `ci`: CI/CD changes
- `perf`: performance improvement
- `ops`: operational or infrastructure workflow change
- `revert`: revert a previous change

Rules:

- Use imperative mood: `fix: handle empty token`, not `fixed` or `fixes`.
- Prefer subjects <= 50 characters; hard max 72 unless matching an existing project style.
- Add a body only when the why, migration path, risk, or non-obvious behavior matters.
- Use `!` or a `BREAKING CHANGE:` footer for breaking changes.
- SemVer mapping: `fix` = PATCH, `feat` = MINOR, breaking change = MAJOR.
- If one message needs multiple unrelated types, split the work into atomic commits.
- Do not add AI attribution unless the repository explicitly requires it.
